  "response_text": "The commercial opens on an open-air boat or ferry deck in bright daylight. Miss Piggy and Kermit the Frog stand near a railing with the Statue of Liberty centered in the distance behind them against a clear blue sky. Miss Piggy is dressed glamorously in a leopard-print fur hat and matching coat, with long blonde hair and a pearl necklace. She faces Kermit, her mouth opening and closing as if speaking, while Kermit, green with his pointed collar, turns his large eyes toward her and then toward the skyline. A small Mastercard logo appears at the lower right of the image.\n\nAs they continue looking at each other and at the statue, white text begins to appear at the lower left: “trip…” Kermit stands with one hand at his side, while Miss Piggy tilts her head and looks pleased. Fozzie Bear, an orange-brown furry bear wearing his familiar brown hat, steps in from the right, looming close in the foreground and facing them. More Muppet characters crowd in around Miss Piggy and Kermit on the deck, filling the space. The text expands to “trip…for eight:” and then “trip…for eight: free.” The group becomes lively and packed together: Sam the Eagle, tall and blue-gray with a stern expression, stands at the left; Animal, with wild red hair and a wide open mouth, pops up near the center; other Muppets press in around Kermit and Miss Piggy, their faces overlapping in a cheerful cluster. Colorful triangular pennant flags hang above them, and the Statue of Liberty remains visible between the characters in the background.\n\nThe setting changes to a city sidewalk lined with stone buildings. Miss Piggy now walks in a white, fashion-forward outfit: a large white hat, white oval sunglasses, and a white coat with fluffy fur trim at the shoulders. She moves among human pedestrians dressed in dark city clothing. Her posture is upright and confident, and her head turns slightly as if leading the way. Behind and around her, people pass by on the busy street.\n\nAs Miss Piggy moves out of view, a large collection of shopping bags and stacked gift boxes fills the sidewalk. The packages are in pastel and bright colors—pink, cream, green, white, and multicolored—with ribbons and handles. The white lower-left text reads “shopping:” and then changes to “shopping: free.” Muppet characters are partly hidden by the tall piles of bags and boxes. Fozzie’s orange face appears near the center behind the packages, and Kermit peeks in from the right, looking up from beside a cluster of bags. The packages are so numerous that they obscure much of the group, suggesting an exaggerated shopping spree.\n\nA wider city street appears in full daylight, with tall buildings on both sides, American flags hanging from facades, and a bus stopped in the distance. Crowds of pedestrians cross the street, while yellow taxis and dark cars line the foreground and sides. The group of Muppets and shoppers is visible on the right side amid the flow of people and traffic, still surrounded by shopping bags. The text “shopping: free” remains at the lower left.\n\nThe scene moves to nighttime outside a theater. Kermit stands in front of a lit marquee with a sign reading “THE PRODUCERS,” with smaller text above that appears to reference Mel Brooks. Warm theater lights glow along the canopy and building facade. Kermit is dressed formally in a black suit or tuxedo with a white shirt and black tie. He looks upward toward the sign and then faces forward, appearing ready for an evening out. White text at the lower left reads “entertainment.”\n\nInside a warmly lit restaurant or supper-club setting, the Muppets sit together around tables with glasses, candles, and plates. The room has dark wood tones and a polished, upscale atmosphere. In the foreground, Miss Piggy and Kermit sit close together, leaning cheek to cheek. Miss Piggy, now in a soft pink-and-white look with long blonde hair, wraps herself affectionately near Kermit, who sits beside her with a relaxed smile. Behind them, Fozzie, Animal, Sam the Eagle, and other Muppets gather at the table, some facing forward and others turned toward one another. At the right, an older male waiter in a black vest, white shirt, and bow tie stands holding a small notepad or check folder, observing the group. White text across the lower left reads, “people who make you feel warm and fuzzy:” and then adds “priceless.”\n\nThe final images show the group inside a yellow taxi at night. The Muppets are crowded into the back seat, visible through the taxi’s side windows; Animal’s red hair, Kermit’s green face, and other familiar figures appear in the cramped interior. Fine-print legal text runs along the bottom of the screen. Over the taxi window and yellow body, the word “Priceless” appears in a white handwritten script, tying the busy city outing and time with friends back to the Mastercard “Priceless” theme.",
